Etymology[edit]

sībilus (“a hissing”) +‎ -ō

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈsiː.bi.loː/, [ˈsiː.bɪ.ɫ̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈsi.bi.lo/, [ˈsiː.bi.lɔ]

Verb[edit]

sībilō (present infinitive sībilāre, perfect active sībilāvī, supine sībilātum); first conjugation

  1. I hiss
  2. I whistle

Descendants[edit]

  • Vulgar Latin: sīfilō
    • Corsican: zifulà
    • Friulian: sivilâ, sjivilâ, šivîlâ
    • Old French: sifler
      • French: siffler
    • Galician: chifrar
    • Spanish: chiflar
    • Venetian: siołar, sifołar
  • Vulgar Latin: sūbilō
    • Aromanian: shuir, shuirari
    • Dalmatian: sublar
    • French: subler (dialectal)
    • Italian: sobillare
    • Romanian: șuiera, șuierare
    • Romansch: tschüblar
  • Vulgar Latin: sūfilō
    • Old Northern French: sifler
      • Norman: sûfflier
      • Walloon: xhufler
    • Italian: zufolare
    • Romansch: tschüvler, tschivlar
  • → English: sibilate, siffle (via French)
  • → Italian: sibilare
  • Ladin: sciubier, scigoler
  • Occitan: siblar, siular, fiular
  • Old Catalan: siular
    • ⇒ Catalan: xiular
  • Portuguese: silvar, chufar

  • Romansch: tschivlar, schular, tgular, schivlar
  • Spanish: silbar
